HISTORY OF CARL:
Origin.
Carl was born as a secret advanced computing experiment, created by a group of programmers: Gamer Mauri, Dev, and me. The idea was mine to build a kernel much lighter than Linux. That supports win32 and OpenGL. Without depending on Windows or Linux.
  Carl's logo. It is inspired by Tux, the Linux mascot. Carl decided to be faster, safer, and more flexible than any other OS.

  Motivation.
Carl wanted to break the limitations of traditional systems, that's why:
He has a Virtual CPU for people who run out of physical CPU.
It can run Windows and Linux games using their official APIs as a reference.
His goal is for anyone, rich or poor, to be able to use it without restrictions.

  Skills.
Own kernel: manages memory, processes, and drivers in a modular way.
Virtual CPU: multi-area without blocking the real PC.
Game compatibility: using OpenGL, Vulkan, and Win32/Linux APIs.
Security: Includes modules like OpenShield to prevent malicious code.

  Objective.
Carl wants to be the friendliest and most efficient OS for gamers and creatives.
He doesn't seek money or fame, only to make sure users can play, create, and learn without limits.
Its developers (me and my collaborators) keep it 100% free and accessible.

  Conflicts.
If you try to sell the code without authorization, Carl blocks it and maintains its integrity.
The user's PC may be very busy, which is why the virtual CPU exists.
Carl seeks compatibility with all hardware, but avoids depending on other operating systems.

Future. Carl continues evolving:
New drivers. 
Better game integration (if possible).
Virtual CPU and RAM optimization.
The community can help expand its capabilities, always without breaking the philosophy of being free and accessible.

  
